# Spec 003 — Commute depth: adjustable time + typical variation

Status: Draft
Owner: <you>
Related: builds on 001-mvp R3/R5 (single hard-coded 30-min isochrone)

## Overview

The MVP draws one hard-coded 30-minute drive-time contour. This feature makes
the commute layer interactive and honest about traffic: the user can **adjust the
commute time** (15 / 30 / 45 / 60 min), and the map shows the **typical variation**
in reachable area across times of day — the same contour under **off-peak**,
**typical**, and **peak** departure — plus a numeric summary of the spread.

## Context

- All contours come from the Mapbox **Isochrone API** (backend-only; token never
  client-side — 001 R5). Verified working with the project token:
  `mapbox/driving-traffic` profile + `depart_at` (ISO 8601) both return 200.
- The layer models drive time **leaving the workplace** (an isochrone is computed
  outward from the work point at the departure time). Variation = the same
  N-minute contour at three `driving-traffic` departures: **light traffic (~8pm,
  largest reach)**, **midday**, and **evening rush (~5pm, smallest reach)** — the
  PM rush is the genuine outbound-congestion low (measured), not the AM, which is
  the uncongested reverse commute.
- Because congestion is directional, raw contours can cross; the bands are
  **clipped to strictly nest** (peak ⊆ typical ⊆ off-peak), so an inner band reads
  as "reachable even in worse traffic." The off-peak↔peak gap is the variation.
- Per-ZIP, time-of-day *inbound* (home→work) times would need the Matrix API's
  `depart_at`, which returns 422 (beta) on the project token — deferred.
- The Isochrone API caps each contour at **60 minutes**, so the time control tops
  out at 60. Per-ZIP numeric std-dev (Matrix API) is out of scope — its `depart_at`
  is beta and it needs many more calls.

## Requirements

- **R1 — Adjustable commute time.** The user selects the contour time from
  discrete steps **15 / 30 / 45 / 60** minutes; the map updates to that time.
  Selection is bounded (no free-drag spamming of the API).
- **R2 — Time-of-day variation bands.** For the selected time, the map overlays
  three contours — off-peak / typical / peak departure — visually distinct and
  layered so the peak (smallest) reads on top of the off-peak (largest).
- **R3 — Numeric variation summary.** A readout shows the reach spread, e.g.
  off-peak vs peak reachable area (mi²) and the peak shrink (%).
- **R4 — Key safety preserved.** The token stays server-side; the client only
  passes `lat`/`lon`/`minutes` to its own origin (001 R5 intact).
- **R5 — Graceful degradation.** If traffic/`depart_at` is unavailable (tier) or a
  scenario call fails, the map still renders the scenarios that succeed; with no
  token (fixture mode) it shows a single typical contour and no variation summary.

## Non-functional / Constraints

- Bounded Mapbox usage: ≤ 3 Isochrone calls per (location, time); results cached.
- `depart_at` timestamps are future weekday occurrences in the metro's local
  timezone (America/Los_Angeles), computed server-side.
- Re-selecting a time is a fetch + repaint; no full page reload.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Choosing 15 / 30 / 45 / 60 redraws the contour(s) for that time.
- [ ] Three departure scenarios render as distinct, layered bands (peak on top).
- [ ] A summary shows off-peak vs peak reach (mi²) and the peak shrink %.
- [ ] With the token unset, a single contour still renders and the app works.
- [ ] The browser Network tab shows no Mapbox token in any client request.
- [ ] `pytest` (backend) and `npm run test` (frontend) pass.

## Out of Scope (explicit)

- Per-ZIP commute std-dev via the Matrix API (depart_at beta; many calls).
- Times above 60 min (Isochrone API limit) and distance-based contours.
- User-chosen departure time / day; scenarios are fixed representative windows.
- Transit/walking/cycling modes.

## Verification notes

Criteria trace: time control → R1; bands → R2; summary → R3; token absence → R4;
fixture/partial-failure → R5. Verify against a running build with a live token;
the implementing agent does not self-certify done.
